aline vent conditions, anoxic, H2-rich"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface hydrogenation of CO2 gives surface-bound formyl equivalents that are released as formate.", "reasoning": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction on Fe-S minerals is a core vent process and provides reduced C1 feedstocks for downstream prebiotic synthesis; this is consistent with iron-sulfur world chemistry and vent CO2-to-formate reduction frameworks (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Cody et al., 2000)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type generation of formaldehyde-equivalent carbonyls", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/elemental iron", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subseafloor reducing conditions; product interpreted as transferable formaldehyde-equivalent feedstock"}, "mechanism": "Sequential reduction of carbon oxides on iron-rich mineral surfaces yields small aldehydic products including formaldehyde-equivalent species.", "reasoning": "Reduced hydrothermal mixtures are reported to contain formaldehyde relevant to amino-acid-forming chemistry, while magnetite/Fe0 are standard hydrothermal catalysts for carbon oxide reduction; exact formaldehyde production is context dependent, so this connection is a literature-grounded but simplified connector (Shock & Schulte, 1998; source set summarized in the knowledge-base report citing reduced hydrothermal mixtures and formaldehyde relevance, including source 2595)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Surface cyanide photochemistry to HCN pool", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed evapo