cause it uses glycolonitrile, glyoxylate, pyruvate, and oxaloacetate, all of which are highlighted in the knowledge base. Fe2+-driven protometabolic oxaloacetate formation is plausible. Still, the route breaks down at the undefined biochemical convergence to a proline precursor pool and the unsupported final stereoselective cyclization.', 'The pyruvate-glyoxylate convergence to oxaloacetate is a strong protometabolic motif and consistent with literature on Fe2+-driven networks. However, this pathway does not yet provide a convincing chemically explicit bridge from oxaloacetate to a cyclic amino acid. The generic precursor pool obscures the true bottleneck.', 'This shorter C1-centered route benefits from plausible early hydrothermal carbon fixation and robust Strecker glycine formation. But the carbon-accounting and mechanistic detail from C1 chemistry into a C5 cyclic amino acid are too compressed. The final proline steps remain the major unresolved issue.', 'The HCN-centered branch recognizes an important literature hub, but it depends critically on an implausible formaldehyde-to-HCN step and an undefined final assembly. Glycolonitrile chemistry itself is well grounded; the rest of the route is not sufficiently specified to justify target formation.', 'Reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine is plausible and literature-consistent for prebiotic amino acid generation. However, the stated support of an alanine-rich amino pool does not establish a direct route to proline. The path appears chemically disconnected from the actual cyclic amino acid bottleneck.', 'This surface-to-hydrothermal return branch captures the intended environmental interconnection well and uses literature-relevant hubs such as glyoxylate and oxaloacetate. Its weakness is again the missing mechanistic detail for conversion of these hubs into a specific proline precursor and then L-proline.', 'This reduced hydrothermal mixture route is motivated by literature noting formaldehyde addition to glycine can yield proline among other products in high-concentration experiments. That gives it some relevance, but it is too abbreviated and lacks explicit intermediate definition. The claim of ending in L-proline is not justified from the cited evidence.', 'As a whole-network pathway, this is the best expression of the design goal: it is connected, has multiple hubs, includes convergence, and captures hydrothermal-to-surface-to-biochemical flow well. It aligns reasonably with literature for precursor formation: glycolonitrile, glyoxylate, pyruvate, oxaloacetate, and glycine are all appropriate. However, the actual proline-forming endgame is not experimentally grounded, the HCN generation step is weak, and the final assignment to L-proline rather than a generic/racemic proline product overreaches the available literature.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"L-Proline\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"This network is literature-guided and intentionally distinguishes well-supported precursor chemistry from the unresolved final target-forming step. It builds a connected hydrothermal-to-surface-to-biochemical bipartite graph centered on documented prebiotic hubs relevant to proline chemistry: formate, formaldehyde, HCN, glycolonitrile, glyoxylate, pyruvate, oxaloacetate, glycine, and N-phosphoroaminonitrile intermediates. Multiple convergent pathways generate these hubs across alkaline hydrothermal, tidal-flat, evaporitic-pool, and protometabolic settings. The final appearance of L-proline is represented only through the limited literature-supported evidence that proline can arise in reduced hydrothermal mixtures involving formaldehyde addition to glycine, while explicitly acknowledging in reaction reasoning that direct, mechanistically resolved, stereoselective prebiotic synthesis of free L-proline remains unproven.\",\