bolic coupling of glyoxylate and pyruvate to oxaloacetate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"343K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm to moderate\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+ in solution with iron-mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"approximately 70C; inert atmosphere; protometabolic network conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Fe2+-promoted carbon-carbon coupling within glyoxylate/\u03b1-keto acid networks generates TCA-like intermediates including oxaloacetate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report explicitly identifies Fe2+-catalyzed formation of oxaloacetate and related protometabolic intermediates at 70C under inert atmosphere, and identifies oxaloacetate as relevant to proline precursor chemistry. Mineral agents are specified here to satisfy the network schema while preserving the cited Fe2+-driven chemistry (Muchowska, Varma & Moran, 2019; Stubbs et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Strecker synthesis of glycine from formaldehyde, ammonia, and HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-assisted concentration and adsorption\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic pool or tidal-flat aqueous phase; classic Strecker-type chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia and HCN react with formaldehyde-derived imine/cyanohydrin intermediates, followed by hydrolysis to glycine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The supplie