products.", "reasoning": "The supplied research identifies formaldehyde as a foundational feedstock for proline-relevant chemistry and notes reduced hydrothermal mixtures as plausible environments. Direct quantitative formaldehyde synthesis under exact proline-specific conditions is sparse, so this step is included as a necessary connector grounded in general hydrothermal FTT-style carbon reduction rather than a proline-specific demonstration; it should be regarded as a plausible feeder step, not a resolved proline-forming reaction (Cody et al., 2000; McCollom & Seewald, 2007; speculative connector consistent with the provided hydrothermal framework)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Surface cyanohydrin formation to glycolonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate and sulfide mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic pool or volcanic hot spring; mild concentration by drying"}, "mechanism": "HCN adds to formaldehyde to form the cyanohydrin glycolonitrile.", "reasoning": "The research report identifies formaldehyde plus HCN to glycolonitrile as a critical precursor step for proline-relevant prebiotic chemistry. Mineral assignment follows the mandated surface-mineral schema; the central chemistry is strongly literature-supported even if mineral specificity is broader than the proline literature itself (Patel et al., 2015; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "UV hydration of HCN to formamide", "inputs": ["mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 photocatalyst", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-irradiated shallow pool; anoxic atmosphere"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical hydration/oxidation-state reorganization of HCN gives formamide as a reactive C-N intermediate pool component.", "reasoning": "The supplied framework includes UV photochemistry from HCN to formamide in surface settings. While not a direct proline step, it connects the HCN hub to broader nitrogen chemistry and keeps the graph connected using literature-recognized prebiotic photochemical logic (Saladino et al., 2012; Ferus et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Surface glycolonitrile conversion to glyoxylate-class carbonyls", "inputs": ["mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2/borate-assisted photochemical and aqueous transformation", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV exposure; wet-dry cycling; oxidant-free but photochemically active surface environment"}, "mechanism": "Glycolonitrile undergoes hydrolysis/photochemical rearrangement toward glyoxylate-class aldehyde-acid products.", "reasoning": "The research identifies glycolonitrile as a major proline-relevant precursor and also highlights glyoxylate as an important small-molecule feedstock in prebiotic networks. The exact glycolonitrile-to-glyoxylate route is not singled out in the report as a single canonical experiment, so this is a connective but chemically reasonable step bridging two literature-supported hubs (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Patel et al., 2015; speculative connector explicitly added to integrate identified intermediates)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from reduced carbon fixation", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic alkaline/subseafloor hydrothermal conditions"}, "mechanism": "Sequential mineral-catalyzed CO2 reduction and C-C bond formation yield \u03b1-keto acid products including pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate is specifically highlighted in the supplied hydrothermal framework as a product of CO2 + H2 chemistry on magnetite/greigite and is a central metabolic hub for amino acid chemistry. Including it is therefore directly required by the prompt and consistent with hydrothermal protometabolic literature (Cody et al., 2000; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Fe2+-driven protometabolic coupling of glyoxylate and pyruvate to oxaloacetate", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "343K", "pressure": "1 atm to moderate", "catalyst": "Fe2+ in solution with iron-mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "approximately 70C; inert atmosphere; protometabolic network conditions"}, "mechanism": "Fe2+-promoted carbon-carbon coupling within glyoxylate/\u03b1-keto acid networks generates TCA-like intermediates including oxaloacetate.", "reasoning": "The report explicitly identifies Fe2+-catalyzed formation of oxaloacetate and related protometabolic intermediates at 70C under inert atmosphere, and identifies oxaloacetate as relevant to proline precursor chemistry. Mineral agents are specified here to satisfy the network schema while preserving the cited Fe2+-driven chemistry (Muchowska, Varma & Moran, 2019; Stubbs et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Surface Strecker synthesis of glycine from formaldehyde, ammonia, and HCN", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_011", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-assisted concentration and adsorption", "aqueous": "true", "other": "e