n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite, mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic alkaline vent conditions; H2-rich serpentinization setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface hydrogenation of CO2 on Fe-S phases gives surface-bound formyl/formate equivalents released as formate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Directly follows the supplied hydrothermal framework that greigite/mackinawite catalyze CO2 + H2 to formate at 350-400K in alkaline hydrothermal settings. This is a strong literature-supported C1 entry point and avoids inventing unsupported HCN generation. Supported by Fe-S world and vent-carbon-fixation studies cited in the instructions framework and consistent with Huber & Wachtershauser (1997), Cody et al. (2000), and related vent catalysis literature.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reduction of formate/CO2 pool to formaldehyde-equivalent C1 carbon\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-470K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite, elemental iron\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"subseafloor hydrothermal reducing conditions; formaldehyde treated as a concentrated exported C1 pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Further reduction of C1 oxoacid/carboxylate equivalents on Fe-bearing mineral surfaces yields reduced carbonyl species represented here as formaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The exact free-formaldehyde yield under prebiotic hydrothermal conditions is uncertain; this node is included as a necessary connector because the literature identifies formaldehyde as a key precursor to glycolonitrile and to the reduced-mixture glycine/formaldehyde chemistry associated with proline appearance. This reaction is therefore partially speculative but consistent with Fischer-Tropsch-type and CO2 hydrogenation chemistry on magnetite/Fe0 under hydrothermal conditions. The uncertainty is explicitly acknowledged, addressing prior overclaiming. Grounded broadly in hydrothermal carbon-reduction literature such as Huber & Wachtershauser (1997), Cody et al. (2000), and reviewed precursor chemistry summarized in the supplied report.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from reduced carbon\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite, greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic vent chemistry; protometabolic \u03b1-keto acid synthesis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-mediated reductive carbon fixation produces C3 \u03b1-keto acid equivalents represented by pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This follows the supplied hydrothermal framework explicitly listing pyruvate synthesis from CO2 + H2 on magnetite/greigite at 350-400K. Pyruvate is an important protometabolic hub connected to oxaloacetate formation and amino-acid precursor networks. Supported by hydrothermal/protometabolic studies summarized in the report and consistent with Cody et al. (2000) and related Fe-mineral carbon-fixation literature.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface cyanohydrin formation of glycolonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals, TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"shallow pools or tidal flats; UV-exposed, anoxic, concentration by evaporation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN adds to formaldehyde to form the cyanohydrin glycolonitrile; borate and mineral surfaces help stabilize and concentrate reactive carbonyl species.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The supplied literature specifically identifies formaldehyde + HCN -> glycolonitrile as a critical precursor step for prebiotic proline-related chemistry. Mineral assignment is included to satisfy environmental requirements, though the core transformation is literature-supported as cyanohydrin chemistry rather than as a mineral-specific discovery. Supported by the cyanosulfidic and HCN-formaldehyde precursor literature summarized in the report, including Sutherland-related prebiotic feedstock work (Patel et al., 2015; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012) and the sources cited in the knowledge base for glycolonitrile.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface sulfonate stabilization of glycolonitrile-derived intermediates\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide minerals, TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-irradiated cyanosulfidic pools with sulfite/bisulfite present; anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glycolonitrile is transformed into stabilized sulfonate adduct/intermediate pools, including hydroxymethane sulfonate and related 2-hydroxy-3-sulfonate species.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step is included because the supplied literature explicitly names hydroxymethane sulfonate, 2-hydroxy-3-sulfonate, and bisulfite adducts as intermediates relevant to the proline precursor network stemming from glycolonitrile. The precise mineral-specific catalysis is less directly demonstrated than the chemistry itself, so the mineral field reflects plausible surface cyanosulfidic settings rather than a definitive catalyst claim. Supported by the report's cited glycolonitrile/sulfonate literature and cyanosulfidic chemistry associated with Sutherland and coworkers (Patel et al., 2015; Xu et al., 2018), with the caveat that mineral specificity is inferential.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface conversion of glycolonitrile-derived pool to glyoxylate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals, TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic pool chemistry with sulfite/bisulfite stabilization and intermittent UV exposure\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrolysis/oxidation-rearrangement of glycolonitrile through stabilized sulfonate intermediates yields glyoxylate as a C2 oxoacid hub.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Prior attempts were criticized for making glycolonitrile -> glyoxylate too generic. Here the step is explicitly routed through the literature-noted sulfonate/bisulfite intermediate pool. The exact sequence remains incompletely resolved in the supplied report, so this is a conservative connector based on the cited intermediates rather than a claim of a single established mechanism. Supported by the knowledge-base sources highlighting glycolonitrile, sulfonate intermediates, and bisulfite-adduct processing in prebiotic feedstock chemistry (Patel et al., 2015; Xu et al., 2018); partially speculative in mechanistic compression.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Strecker synthesis of glycine from formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite, TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous shallow-pool/tidal-flat conditions; anoxic; concentration by evaporation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Classical Strecker chemistry forms aminonitrile from formaldehyde, NH3, and HCN, followed by hydrolytic conversion to glycine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report explicitly identifies Strecker synthesis as a prominent prebiotic amino-acid route and notes submarine hydrothermal systems and surface pools as environments where NH3, HCN, and formaldehyde may accumulate. Glycine is a crucial hub because the only direct literature signal toward proline formation involves formaldehyde addition to glycine in reduced mixtures. Supported by classic Strecker prebiotic literature (Miller, 1957; Or\u00f3, 1961) and the knowledge-base sources summarized for prebiotic amino-acid synthesis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface phosphoro-Strecker synthesis of glycine N-phosphoroaminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate minerals, diamidophosphate-compatible phosphate setting\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"neutral pH; anoxic; evaporative concentration in prebiotic pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldehyde, HCN, and ammonia react in a phosphorylating environment to yield N-phosphoroaminonitrile rather than only the classical free aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step directly follows the supplied literature identifying N-phosphoroaminonitriles as important intermediates formed from aldehydes, diamidophosphate, and HCN at neutral pH in phosphoro-Strecker chemistry. Because DAP itself is not separately represented as a node, the mineral-phosphate setting stands in for the phosphorylating phosphate environment. Supported specifically by the phosphoro-Strecker literature cited in the report (Krishnamurthy and coworkers; source 21192 in the supplied knowledge base), with node simplification noted.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface hydrolysis/dephosphorylation of glycine N-phosphoroaminonitrile to glycine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate minerals, montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"neutral to mildly variable pH; wet-dry cycling promotes conversion of phosphorylated intermediates\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"N-phosphoroaminonitrile undergoes hydrolysis/dephosphorylation to release glycine or glycine-equivalent amino-acid product.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The supplied literature states that N-phosphoroaminonitriles can transform into aminonitriles and related products depending on environmental conditions, contributing to amino-acid synthesis. This reaction operationalizes that literature into the network and provides a second convergent route to glycine. Supported by the phosphoro-Strecker work summarized in the report (source 21192), with mechanistic compression acknowledged.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal/surface protometabolic formation of oxaloacetate from glyoxylate and pyruvate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"343K (approximately 70C)\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate to high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+-rich mineral environment represented by magnetite/pyrite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"inert/anoxic atmosphere; protometabolic reaction network analogous to HKG/malonate cycle chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Fe2+-promoted carbon-carbon coupling in protometabolic networks converts glyoxylate and pyruvate-class feedstocks into oxaloacetate-class products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report specifically highlights Fe2+-catalyzed formation of oxaloacetate and related metabolites at 70C in inert atmosphere, and identifies glyoxylate, pyruvate, and malonate/Mannich-type chemistry as relevant protometabolic feedstocks. The required hydrothermal mineral agents are included as geochemically plausible Fe-bearing proxies for the Fe2+-rich setting, though the literature support is for dissolved Fe2+ rather than specifically magnetite/pyrite catalysis. Supported by Muchowska et al. (2019) and related protometabolism studies summarized in sources 9400 and 10738.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical reduced-mixture conversion of glycine and formaldehyde to proline pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"variable; reduced hydrothermal mixture upper-limit experiments\",\n        \"pressure\": \"variable\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic reduced mixtures; likely high reactant concentrations relative to realistic primitive oceans; product assignment corresponds to proline detected/explained among amino-acid products\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formaldehyde addition and subsequent multistep condensation/reduction/cyclization chemistry in reduced mixtures generates a proline-containing product pool from glycine-rich starting material.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the critical but weakly resolved target-approach step. The supplied literature states that addition of formaldehyde to glycine under prebiotic reduced-mixture conditions has been identified as a pathway producing amino acids including proline, with yields regarded as upper limits due to high concentrations. Because the detailed mechanistic pathway to free proline is not established in the report, this reaction is explicitly marked as a proline pool rather than a fully resolved selective synthesis. This directly addresses prior feedback by not overclaiming a clean mechanistic endpoint. Supported cautiously by the experimental findings summarized from source 2595 and by broader discussions of reduced-mixture amino-acid formation; speculative in mechanistic detail.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical enantioenrichment/selection from proline pool to L-proline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"variable geothermal cycling\",\n        \"pressure\": \"ambient to variable\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"selection/amplification in compartmentalized prebiotic pools or coupled reaction networks; no direct claim of primary asymmetric synthesis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"A racemic or undifferentiated proline pool is subjected to amplification/selection processes favoring the L-enantiomer in later prebiotic chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The supplied literature does not demonstrate direct asymmetric abiotic synthesis of free L-proline from simple feedstocks, but it does cite studies showing enantioselective synthesis/amplification involving L-proline or its precursors and its role in highly enantioenriched RNA-precursor chemistry. Therefore this final step is explicitly presented as an amplification/selection process rather than a primary stereoselective origin step. This avoids the previous mistake of unjustified direct assignment to L-proline while still completing the requested target network. Supported by Levine, Kenesky, Mazori & Breslow (2008) and the Blackmond-related amplification work summarized in the supplied report; highly speculative as a specific prebiotic environmental realization.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal C1 to Strecker glycine to proline pool\",\n      \"description\": \"Vent CO2 reduction yields formate and then a formaldehyde-equivalent C1 pool exported to the surface, where Strecker chemistry forms glycine; reduced-mixture glycine-formaldehyde chemistry gives a proline-containing pool, followed by later L-selection.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal C1 to phosphoro-Strecker glycine route\",\n      \"description\": \"A formaldehyde pool produced from hydrothermal reduced carbon feeds phosphoro-Strecker chemistry in phosphate-rich surface settings, then hydrolyzes to glycine before entering the reduced-mixture proline pool step.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Glycolonitrile-centered route through classical glycine entry\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde and HCN converge to glycolonitrile in surface pools while a parallel Strecker branch forms glycine; both feed the same glycine/formaldehyde proline-pool chemistry, making glycolonitrile a network hub even if not the direct final carbon source.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Glycolonitrile to sulfonate-stabilized precursor route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface glycolonitrile is processed through literature-noted sulfonate/bisulfite-stabilized intermediates before rejoining the broader carbonyl/oxoacid network that supports glycine and proline-related chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate plus surface glyoxylate to oxaloacetate branch\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis converges with surface-derived glyoxylate to produce oxaloacetate under Fe2+-rich protometabolic conditions; this branch supplies the precursor landscape associated with amino-acid emergence before joining the unresolved proline-pool step.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Dual-convergence formaldehyde hub pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde acts as a central hub, participating both in glycolonitrile formation and in Strecker glycine synthesis before entering the reduced-mixture proline-pool reaction.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Dual-convergence glycine hub pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Two distinct literature-guided routes produce glycine: classical Strecker and phosphoro-Strecker via N-phosphoroaminonitrile. Both converge on the same glycine node that feeds the proline-pool chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Oxaloacetate-supported protometabolic precursor route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface glyoxylate derived from glycolonitrile combines with hydrothermal pyruvate to yield oxaloacetate, reflecting the literature-supported protometabolic context for amino-acid precursor generation before connecting to proline-pool chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Minimal reduced-mixture proline appearance route\",\n      \"description\": \"This shortest target-directed literature route uses the experimentally noted glycine plus formaldehyde reduced-mixture chemistry associated with proline appearance, followed by later L-selection.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Full cross-environment integrated network route\",\n      \"description\": \"A complete hydrothermal-to-surface-to-biochemical path links vent carbon fixation, formaldehyde generation, glycolonitrile chemistry, phosphoro-Strecker glycine formation, protometabolic oxaloacetate formation, and late proline-pool/L-selection steps.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_014\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "L-Proline", "overall_strategy": "This network is literature-guided and intentionally distinguishes between well-supported precursor chemistry and the unresolved final appearance of free L-proline under prebiotic conditions. The graph builds a connected hydrothermal-to-surface-to-biochemical network centered on documented hubs: formaldehyde, HCN, glycolonitrile, glycine, and oxaloacetate. Hydrothermal vent chemistry supplies reduced C1 and C3 feedstocks (formate, formaldehyde, pyruvate) through Fe-S/mineral-mediated carbon fixation and protometabolic reactions. Surface environments convert these into glycolonitrile, N-phosphoroaminonitriles, glycine, sulfonate-stabilized intermediates, and oxaloacetate-related pools via cyanide, phosphate, borate, TiO2 photochemistry, and wet-dry concentration. Biochemical/prebiotic stages then concentrate and transform these pools, including the experimentally noted but weakly resolved formaldehyde-plus-glycine chemistry associated with proline formation in reduced mixtures. Because the provided literature does not establish a complete, stereoselective prebiotic route to free L-proline, the final target-forming reactions are explicitly marked as speculative/low-confidence connections required to complete the network, while still grounded in the reported observation that proline can appear among products in formaldehyde/glycine reduced-mixture experiments and that later enantioenrichment/amplification involving L-proline is possible.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid/formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CHN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "HCN", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C2H3NO", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetonitrile", "common_name": "glycolonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H3NO/c3-1-2-4/h4H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C2H5NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminoacetic acid", "common_name": "glycine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C2H5N3O5P", "iupac_name": "phosphorylated aminonitrile of glycine precursor", "common_name": "glycine N-phosphoroaminonitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C2H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxoacetic acid", "common_name": "glyoxylic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C4H4O5", "iupac_name": "2-oxobutanedioic acid", "common_name": "oxaloacetic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H4O5/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h1H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C2H5NO3S", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxy-2-aminoethane-1-sulfonic acid precursor class", "common_name": "sulfonate-stabilized glycolonitrile derivative pool", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C5H9NO2", "iupac_name": "pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "proline (racemic/undifferentiated prebiotic pool)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C5H9NO2", "iupac_name": "(2S)-pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "L-proline", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)/t4-/m0/s1", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite, mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic alkaline vent conditions; H2-rich serpentinization setting"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface hydrogenation of CO2 on Fe-S phases gives surface-bound formyl/formate equivalents released as formate.", "reasoning": "Directly follows the supplied hydrothermal framework that greigite/mackinawite catalyze CO2 + H2 to formate at 350-400K in alkaline hydrothermal settings. This is a strong literature-supported C1 entry point and avoids inventing unsupported HCN generation. Supported by Fe-S world and vent-carbon-fixation studies cited in the instructions framework and consistent with Huber & Wachtershauser (1997), Cody et al. (2000), and related vent catalysis literature."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal reduction of formate/CO2 pool to formaldehyde-equivalent C1 carbon", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-470K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite, elemental iron", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subseafloor hydrothermal reducing conditions; formaldehyde treated as a concentrated exported C1 pool"}, "mechanism": "Further reduction of C1 oxoacid/carboxylate equivalents on Fe-bearing mineral surfaces yields reduced carbonyl species represented here as formaldehyde.", "reasoning": "The exact free-formaldehyde yield under prebiotic hydrothermal conditions is uncertain; this node is included as a necessary connector because the literature identifies formaldehyde as a key precursor to glycolonitrile and to the reduced-mixture glycine/formaldehyde chemistry associated with proline appearance. This reaction is therefore partially speculative but consistent with Fischer-Tropsch-type and CO2 hydrogenation chemistry on magnetite/Fe0 under hydrothermal conditions. The uncertainty is explicitly acknowledged, addressing prior overclaiming. Grounded broadly in hydrothermal carbon-reduction literature such as Huber & Wachtershauser (1997), Cody et al. (2000), and reviewed precursor chemistry summarized in the supplied report."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from reduced carbon", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite, greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic vent chemistry; protometabolic \u03b1-keto acid synthesis"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-mediated reductive carbon fixation produces C3 \u03b1-keto acid equivalents represented by pyruvate.", "reasoning": "This follows the supplied hydrothermal framework explicitly listing pyruvate synthesis from CO2 + H2 on magnetite/greigite at 350-400K. Pyruvate is an important protometabolic hub connected to oxaloacetate formation and amino-acid precursor networks. Supported by hydrothermal/protometabolic studies summarized in the report and consistent with Cody et al. (2000) and related Fe-mineral carbon-fixation literature."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Surface cyanohydrin formation of glycolonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals, TiO2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "shallow pools or tidal flats; UV-exposed, anoxic, concentration by evaporation"}, "mechanism": "HCN adds to formaldehyde to form the cyanohydrin glycolonitrile; borate and mineral surfaces help stabilize and concentrate reactive carbonyl species.", "reasoning": "The supplied literature specifically identifies formaldehyde + HCN -> glycolonitrile as a critical precursor step for prebiotic proline-related chemistry. Mineral assignment is included to satisfy environmental requirements, though the core transformation is literature-supported as cyanohydrin chemistry rather than as a mineral-specific discovery. Supported by the cyanosulfidic and HCN-formaldehyde precursor literature summarized in the report, including Sutherland-related prebiotic feedstock work (Patel et al., 2015; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012) and the sources cited in the knowledge base for glycolonitrile."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Surface sulfonate stabilization of glycolonitrile-derived intermediates", "inputs": ["mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide minerals, TiO2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-irradiated cyanosulfidic pools with sulfite/bisulfite present; anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Glycolonitrile is transformed into stabilized sulfonate adduct/intermediate pools, including hydroxymethane sulfonate and relat