}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Surface Strecker synthesis of glycine from formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite, TiO2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "aqueous shallow-pool/tidal-flat conditions; anoxic; concentration by evaporation"}, "mechanism": "Classical Strecker chemistry forms aminonitrile from formaldehyde, NH3, and HCN, followed by hydrolytic conversion to glycine.", "reasoning": "The report explicitly identifies Strecker synthesis as a prominent prebiotic amino-acid route and notes submarine hydrothermal systems and surface pools as environments where NH3, HCN, and formaldehyde may accumulate. Glycine is a crucial hub because the only direct literature signal toward proline formation involves formaldehyde addition to glycine in reduced mixtures. Supported by classic Strecker prebiotic literature (Miller, 1957; Or\u00f3, 1961) and the knowledge-base sources summarized for prebiotic amino-acid synthesis."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Surface phosphoro-Strecker synthesis of glycine N-phosphoroaminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate minerals, diamidophosphate-compatible phosphate setting", "aqueous": "true", "other": "neutral pH; anoxic; evaporative concentration in prebiotic pools"}, "mechanism": "Aldehyde, HCN, and ammonia react in a phosphorylating environment to yield N-phosphoroaminonitrile rather than only the classical free aminonitrile.", "reasoning": "This step directly follows the supplied literature identifying N-phosphoroaminonitriles as important intermediates formed from aldehydes, diamidophosphat